//
// Document, DocumentRequirement, and DocumentReview are covered by this
// checkpoint — the Document Schema Foundation checkpoint. Stage A first
// added this schema and D-018 without creating or applying any migration.
// Migration `20260717073151_document_schema_foundation` was subsequently
// generated, reviewed, and hand-augmented with the six constraints D-018
// requires (`document_requirement_target_exclusive`,
// `document_context_exclusive`, `document_uploader_path_exclusive`,
// `document_version_positive`, `document_previous_not_self`, and
// `document_review_reason_required` — see each model's doc comment below
// for every constraint's exact text). `prisma migrate status` confirmed
// on July 20, 2026 that this migration is applied to the local
// `heritage_v3_dev` database — 10 migrations found, database schema up to
// date — it has not been applied to staging or production regardless
// (blueprint Sections 4.2-4.6,
// 12.1-12.3, 13.1, 13.3, 13.4, 13.7, 14.7;
// docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-018). Per D-018: each `Document` row
// represents one immutable uploaded file/version — a replacement creates a
// new `Document` linked back through `previousDocumentId`, and the
// replaced row is retained, never deleted or mutated; no separate
// `DocumentVersion` model is introduced. `Document.status` is deliberately
// not a stored field and no `DocumentStatus` enum is modeled — operational
// status is derived by the future service/repository layer in this exact
// priority order: (a) if another `Document` references this row through
// `previousDocumentId` — equivalently, this row's `replacementDocument`
// reverse relation is non-null — this (older) row is SUPERSEDED/REPLACED,
// regardless of any `DocumentReview` it may also carry; (b) otherwise, if
// this `Document` has no `DocumentReview` rows at all, it is
// PENDING_REVIEW; (c) otherwise, its status is the latest
// `DocumentReview.outcome`, with "latest" selected deterministically using
// `reviewedAt DESC, createdAt DESC, id DESC` — a service/repository
// ordering rule, not a new database constraint or index requirement.
// `DocumentReviewOutcome` is the only closed enum this checkpoint adds,
// taken directly from blueprint Section 14.7's own closed three-value list
// ("approved, rejected, replacement requested"). `documentRequirementId`
// is nullable — proactive or ad-hoc uploads are permitted, and a document
// counts toward a formal requirement only when explicitly linked. Every
// `Document` has a required `clientId`
// and may additionally target at most one of `bookingId`/`visaCaseId`
// (never both) — a client-only document with both null is permitted.
// Every `DocumentRequirement` targets exactly one of `bookingId`/
// `visaCaseId` (never neither, never both). Cross-row invariants this
// schema cannot enforce — a linked Document's target/client must agree
// with its DocumentRequirement's; a replacement must preserve the same
// client/context/requirement lineage and increment `version` by exactly
// one; no long replacement cycle may form — are explicitly deferred to
// mandatory service-layer verification, the same way this schema already
// defers analogous cross-row checks for Booking.clientId and
// VisaCase.clientId. Migration `20260717073151_document_schema_foundation`
// now exists and contains this section's generated tables, enum, indexes,
// and foreign keys, hand-augmented with the six D-018 CHECK constraints
// noted above — `docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md` remains the source for
// verified environment/migration-application status, mirroring how the
// Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint's own migration section documents
// the same discipline. In particular, this checkpoint deliberately does
// NOT implement:
//
// - VisaRequirement — remains deferred (D-018); see the VisaCase section
//   above for the resolved boundary between it and DocumentRequirement.
// - ActivityLog-based access/download logging (blueprint Section 12.3's
//   "access and download audit logs for every document") — deferred to
//   Phase 4 implementation (D-018); must exist before document
//   access/download endpoints are considered complete. The existing
//   `AuditLog` model remains scoped to sensitive/security-relevant staff
//   actions and must not be repurposed as the routine download-event
//   store.
// - Storage-provider/bucket identifier, checksum, malware-scan-status, and
//   any document-content field — this checkpoint uses only the storage
//   metadata boundary already established by `MessageAttachment`
//   (`storageKey`, `fileName`, `mimeType`, `fileSizeBytes`); none of these
//   additional fields is blueprint-required, so none is added (D-018).
// - Document/DocumentRequirement/DocumentReview repository and service
//   layers, API routes, admin dashboard and client portal UI, document
//   upload/preview/download flows, malware scanning, signed/expiring
//   download-link issuance (Section 12.3; ADR-001), and tests/seed data —
//   all deferred to future checkpoints.
//
// PaymentPlan, Installment, Payment, PaymentStatusHistory,
// PaymentAllocation, PaymentAllocationReversal, PaymentRefund,
// PaymentRefundAllocation, and Receipt are covered by this checkpoint —
// the Payment Schema Foundation checkpoint, Stage A (schema-and-decision-
// documentation only — schema.prisma and this decisions-log entry, no
// migration created or applied) (blueprint Sections 4.2-4.7, 5.1-5.2,
// 11.1-11.7, 13.4, 13.6, 14.5, 14.6; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md
// D-019). D-002 (currency strategy) is refined, not superseded, by this
// checkpoint: the original PHP-only-MVP proposal remains recorded
// verbatim, and D-019 records the actual approved refinement — each
// Booking selects exactly one currency (PHP and USD are supported
// examples), every amount within that Booking uses it, and mixed-
// currency/exchange-rate handling inside one Booking is deferred.
//
// `Booking.totalAmount`/`currencyCode` are added by this checkpoint, both
// nullable — see the Booking model doc comment below for the exact
// backward-compatibility rationale (no existing Booking-creation code
// path populates either field yet) and the service invariants that
// govern them (both must exist before a PaymentPlan may be created;
// neither may change once a PaymentPlan or Payment exists for that
// Booking).
//
// `PaymentPlan` belongs directly to `Booking` (`bookingId @unique` — one
// plan per Booking for the MVP) and does not duplicate `totalAmount`,
// `currencyCode`, or a separate deposit-amount field; a deposit is
// represented as an `Installment` with `isDeposit = true` instead (at
// most one per plan, enforced by a migration-only partial unique index —
// see the Installment model doc comment). `Installment` carries no
// stored status and no waiver fields — payment state is fully derived by
// the future service layer from allocations, refunds, due date, and
// amount (D-019), and no approved requirement supports installment
// waivers, so none is added.
//
// `Payment` targets its `Booking` and `Client` directly — never an
// `installmentId` — and carries no inline confirm/reject/reverse/refund
// timestamp, actor, or reason field; every status transition is instead
// recorded on the new append-only `PaymentStatusHistory` (mirroring
// `BookingStatusHistory`'s convention exactly), which the future service
// layer must write in the same transaction as every `Payment.status`
// update. `PaymentAllocation` links a `Payment` to the `Installment`(s)
// it covers — always a positive amount, append-only, never signed and
// never directly correctable in place; a misallocation is corrected by
// writing a `PaymentAllocationReversal` (a complete, one-time reversal of
// a single allocation) and then creating new, separate positive
// `PaymentAllocation` rows — never by mutating or deleting the original.
// A confirmed amount left unallocated to any Installment is unapplied
// Booking credit and is never automatically applied to a future
// Installment (D-019).
//
// `PaymentRefund` is a separate, append-only record — a row exists only
// once money has actually been returned, so this checkpoint models no
// "pending refund" state. Multiple partial refunds against one Payment
// are supported; a Payment stays `CONFIRMED` while partially refunded and
// becomes `REFUNDED` only once cumulative refunds equal its full amount
// (D-019) — this refines, without contradicting, blueprint Section 11.2's
// "Refunded" row, which was worded at the whole-payment-status level
// before partial refunds were an approved feature; see the amendment this
// checkpoint also makes to docs/HERITAGE_V3_PROJECT_BLUEPRINT.md's
// Payments section. `PaymentRefundAllocation` links a `PaymentRefund` to
// the specific `PaymentAllocation` row(s) it reduces, preserving exactly
// which Installment's balance reopens because of a refund; any refunded
// amount not linked to an allocation is a refund from unapplied Booking
// credit. The corrected net-contribution formula — `Payment.amount -
// completed refunds` when `status` is `CONFIRMED` or `REFUNDED`, else
// `0` — is documented in full, with worked examples, in D-019; it
// specifically fixes an earlier draft's defect where a fully refunded
// Payment produced a negative contribution instead of exactly zero.
//
// `PaymentStatus` is the exact seven-value closed list from blueprint
// Section 11.2's table (`PENDING`, `CONFIRMED`, `REJECTED`, `CANCELLED`,
// `FAILED`, `REFUNDED`, `REVERSED`) — no `VOIDED` or `PARTIALLY_REFUNDED`
// value is added; a partial refund is represented by a `PaymentRefund`
// row against a still-`CONFIRMED` Payment, not by a new status.
//
// `Receipt` is an immutable historical snapshot (`amount`/`currencyCode`
// captured at issuance, no `updatedAt`) — one per Payment
// (`paymentId @unique`), issued only for a validly confirmed Payment, and
// preserved unchanged after any later reversal or refund of that Payment
// (blueprint Section 11.5's "original receipts... are never deleted").
// No receipt-number prefix format is enforced — only uniqueness.
//
// `Document.paymentId` (nullable) lets a client-submitted payment-proof
// upload reuse the existing Document/DocumentReview machinery rather than
// a parallel review model — the existing `document_context_exclusive`
// CHECK is widened from two columns to three
// (`num_nonnulls("bookingId", "visaCaseId", "paymentId") <= 1`) by the
// same mechanical pattern already used for the Visa Case Schema
// Foundation's widening. See the DocumentReview model doc comment below
// for the narrow role-boundary amendment this checkpoint makes:
// Finance/Accounting may review a Document only when its `paymentId` is
// non-null — a structural check, not a `category` string match, since
// `Document.category` remains free-text with no closed list or CHECK
// constraint (blueprint Section 12.1). No `PAYMENT_PROOF` category
// constant or CHECK is invented.
//
// Every write path (allocate, reverse an allocation, refund, confirm,
// reverse a Payment) that the future service layer implements must use a
// unique, caller-supplied `idempotencyKey`, exactly mirroring how
// `bookings/service.ts`'s existing `createBooking` already handles a
// unique-constraint race on `bookingReference`/`proposalVersionId` — this
// checkpoint adds the `idempotencyKey` columns those future services will
// rely on, but implements none of the retry logic itself.
//
// Deliberately out of scope for this checkpoint (Stage A and beyond):
// - `PaymentAdjustment` — not modeled until its exact balance effect is
//   approved (D-019); a standalone correction/adjustment concept remains
//   deferred rather than guessed at.
// - Payment or PaymentPlan as a `StaffAssignment` target — Payment
//   authorization derives entirely from the existing Booking-level
//   assignment (D-019); no new target column is added to
//   `StaffAssignment`.
// - Any payment-gateway/processor field (transaction reference, gateway
//   status, etc.) — payment processor selection itself remains an open
//   ADR-001 decision ("Items Intentionally Deferred"); nothing here
//   assumes one.
// - Mixed-currency or exchange-rate handling within a single Booking —
//   explicitly deferred by D-019; every amount within a Booking uses that
//   Booking's single selected `currencyCode`.
// - An installment-status enum and automatic credit-to-installment
//   allocation — both explicitly excluded by D-019; installment state is
//   fully derived, and unapplied credit is never auto-applied.
// - The refund documentation type (a refund reference, credit note, or
//   equivalent client-facing document, blueprint Section 11.5/16.2) —
//   remains open; `PaymentRefund` is a structured internal financial
//   record only, not automatically that document (D-019).
// - A post-approval Installment amendment/correction workflow — whether
//   `Installment.amount`/`dueDate` may be directly mutated after
//   `PaymentPlan` approval (with an `AuditLog` entry) or must instead
//   follow its own append-only correction pattern is left open (D-019);
//   no `PaymentPlan`/`Installment` versioning is invented either way.
// - PaymentPlan/Installment/Payment/PaymentStatusHistory/
//   PaymentAllocation/PaymentAllocationReversal/PaymentRefund/
//   PaymentRefundAllocation/Receipt repository and service layers, API
//   routes, admin dashboard and client portal UI, malware
//   scanning/signed-URL issuance for payment-proof documents, and
//   tests/seed data — all deferred to future checkpoints.
//
// Notification is covered by this checkpoint — the Notification Schema
// Foundation checkpoint, Stage A (schema-and-decision-documentation only —
// schema.prisma and this decisions-log entry, no migration created or
// applied) (blueprint Section 14.9; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md
// D-020). Blueprint Section 14.9 gives Notification only a one-sentence
// description ("a system-generated alert to a User (staff or client) about
// a relevant event") with no field list, type list, or delivery model —
// see the Notification model doc comment near AuditLog above for the full
